{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637090"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:37:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:37:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17629"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17629"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.15,0.1,0.1,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10343"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71808"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10343"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17629"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57297"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10039"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24240"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71808"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe small intestinal epithelium absorbs different monosaccharides through distinct transport mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this transport mechanism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["All monosaccharides cross by simple diffusion","All monosaccharides require direct ATP-dependent transport","Fructose and glucose use identical sodium-dependent carriers","Galactose uses facilitated diffusion while glucose requires active transport","Glucose and galactose use sodium cotransport while fructose uses facilitated diffusion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe absorption of monosaccharides involves multiple transport proteins. \u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose and galactose use sodium cotransport while fructose uses facilitated diffusion\u003C/strong\u003E. Specifically, SGLT1 transports glucose and galactose across the apical membrane using the sodium gradient created by sodium-potassium ATPase. Fructose enters via GLUT5 transporters. All monosaccharides exit through basolateral GLUT2 transporters into the bloodstream.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGalactose uses facilitated diffusion while glucose requires active transport\u003C/strong\u003E - Both molecules use the same sodium-dependent mechanism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll monosaccharides cross by simple diffusion\u003C/strong\u003E - Specific protein transporters are essential for absorption\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll monosaccharides require direct ATP-dependent transport\u003C/strong\u003E - ATP is only needed indirectly to maintain the sodium gradient\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFructose and glucose use identical sodium-dependent carriers\u003C/strong\u003E - Fructose uses the sodium-independent GLUT5 transporter\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glucose and galactose absorption in the small intestine occurs via sodium-dependent cotransport through SGLT1.","Fructose crosses the intestinal epithelium through GLUT5 transporters by facilitated diffusion.","All absorbed monosaccharides exit enterocytes via GLUT2 transporters in the basolateral membrane."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57297"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17629"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57297"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T16:06:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T16:07:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10343"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71808"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"